english:
  title: Inscription on the Poetry Manuscript of Kim Gahaeng
  author: Lee Suingin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The three hundred poems of the Classic of Poetry have become the foundation of poetic art. The Sage once reflected upon them, saying: "The 'Ospreys' brings joy without excess, sorrow without harm." And again he said: "All three hundred poems may be summed up in a single phrase: let your thoughts harbor no deception." This is the ultimate truth in judging poetry.

    Though the Way of Poetry has undergone endless transformations, critics often ignore the foundation of genuine feeling and pursuit only the felicity or clumsiness of individual phrases and characters. I have long lamented this fault. Kim Gahaeng of Kyeongju showed me his poetry manuscript, and I found the language refined and natural, the imagery profound and far-reaching. In eight or nine of every ten poems, I discerned loyalty to the sovereign, love for parents, respect for teachers, and devotion to friends—all matters touching upon the moral instruction of the world. Upon reading these works, I was moved to straighten my robes and exclaim: "Truly so! Truly so!"

    Alas, poetry cannot deceive! The simple folk cannot conceal their lustful nature beneath their artless speech, nor could Cao Cao's famous song hide his treacherous designs. How then can one say that poetry does not spring from the deepest nature of a person's heart? Gahaeng has studied with me for ten years now. I have long cherished him for his character, yet poetry is but a secondary pursuit for him—and yet even here he achieves such excellence. What accumulates within must manifest without; this is the way of things. How can I not hold him in ever greater esteem?

    Yet Gahaeng should not rest content with this. In his studies he knows how to advance but not when to stop. Therefore I inscribe upon his manuscript the words by which the Sage judged poetry, saying: "When the work of learning finally reaches the point where your mind harbors no crookedness, then poetry itself becomes superfluous to discuss." Let Gahaeng heed this and strive onward.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Ospreys' (Guan Ju) is the opening poem of the Classic of Poetry, traditionally cited by Confucius as exemplifying proper emotional restraint in art.
    - '"Think no evil" (si wu xie) is Confucius''s famous summary of the entire Classic of Poetry in a single phrase, emphasizing the moral foundation of genuine poetry.'
    - Cao Cao (155-220 CE), known as Cao Mengde, was a military commander whose poem 'Short Song' is referenced here as an example of how true feelings inevitably surface through poetry despite attempts at concealment.
    - Kyeongju (鷄林) is an ancient name for Gyeongju, a major cultural center in Korea.
